    "024ab42c-2918-48a2-8db2-1dacbf8077b3": {
      "id": "024ab42c-2918-48a2-8db2-1dacbf8077b3",
      "message": {
        "id": "024ab42c-2918-48a2-8db2-1dacbf8077b3",
        "author": {
          "role": "assistant",
          "name": null,
          "metadata": {}
        },
        "create_time": 1777135684.815391,
        "update_time": null,
        "content": {
          "content_type": "text",
          "parts": [
            "You’re right to push back on that phrasing—“extending” implies a methodological or theoretical contribution that you’re not actually making.\n\nHere are a few alternatives that keep the intent precise while sounding natural in an academic discussion:\n\n- **“Building on this perspective,”**  \n- **“In addition to this model,”**  \n- **“Complementing this model,”** ← probably the cleanest fit  \n- **“Alongside this model,”**  \n- **“Rather than relying solely on this model,”** ← slightly more assertive  \n- **“To supplement this model,”**\n\nA polished revision of your sentence could be:\n\n> “Complementing this model, we recommend identifying an appropriate tradeoff empirically by measuring user task performance~\\cite{lam2011empirical}, such as task completion accuracy or time, across different analysis tasks.”\n\nIf you want it to feel a bit more grounded and less “AI-polished,” this version reads very naturally in a discussion section:\n\n> “In addition to this model, we recommend identifying an appropriate tradeoff empirically by measuring user task performance~\\cite{lam2011empirical}, such as task completion accuracy or time, across different analysis tasks.”"
          ]
        },
